several places in northern France, such as Nogent-le-Sec and Nogent-sur-Eure (both in Eure), Nogent-le-Phaye, Nogent-le-Roi, and Nogent-le-Rotrou (all in Eure-et-Loir), Nogent-l'Abbesse (Marne), Nogent-l'Artaud (Aisne), and in particular Nogent-sur-Oise (Oise), named with Latin <i>Novientum</i>, apparently an altered form of a Gaulish name meaning ‘new settlement’.","Irish: in Ireland, this is generally the Norman name, but it was also adopted for <b>Mag Uinseanáin</b> (formerly Anglicized as <i>McGunshenan</i>, a variant of   Gilsenan  ), on the grounds of a fancied resemblance between <i>Uinseanán</i> and <i>Uinnseadún</i>.","History: The Anglo-Norman family of this name is descended from Fulke de Bellesme, lord of Nogent in Normandy, who was granted large estates around Winchester after the Conquest. His great-grandson was Hugh de Nugent (died 1213), who went to Ireland with Hugh de Lacy, and was granted lands in Bracklyn, County Westmeath. The family formed itself into a clan on the Irish model, of which the chief bore the hereditary title of <i>Uinsheadun</i> (Irish <i>Uinnseadún</i>), from their original seat at Winchester. They have been Earls of Westmeath since 1621. The name is now a common one in Ireland, and has been adopted there by some who have no connection with the clan."]},{"name":"Noojin","meanings":["Altered form of Irish and English   Newgent  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Newent was born about 1325, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. She married RObert Clipsby. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"abt. 1325–":"umbes 1325–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1325":"1325","abt. 1325":"umbes 1325","1320":"1320","<1360>":"1360","1360":"1360","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Clipsby, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abt. 1325–":"noin 1325–Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1325":"1325","abt. 1325":"noin 1325","1320":"1320","<1360>":"1360","1360":"1360","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Clipsby, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"abt. 1325–":"environ 1325–Décédée","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1360–Male":"1360–Décédé","1325–Female":"1325–Décédée","1325":"1325","abt. 1325":"environ 1325","1320":"1320","<1360>":"1360","1360":"1360","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Clipsby, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Agnes Newent est née environ 1325, à Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé RObert Clipsby. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"abt. 1325–":"um 1325–Verstorben","1320–Male":"1320–Verstorben","1360–Male":"1360–Verstorben","1325–Female":"1325–Verstorben","1325":"1325","abt. 1325":"um 1325","1320":"1320","<1360>":"1360","1360":"1360","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Clipsby, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Agnes Newent wurde um 1325 in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hat RObert Clipsby gehe